<section id="todays-topics-git-and-quarto" class="level1">
<h1>Today’s topics: Git and Quarto</h1>
<p><a href="fire_1.JPG" class="lightbox" data-gallery="quarto-lightbox-gallery-1"><img src="jay-uu.github.io/jayblog/posts/image-posts/fire_1.JPG" class="img-fluid"></a></p>
<section id="git" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="git">Git</h2>
<p>Samuel taught us how to cooperate on a git project. I’ve worked a lot with git alone, keeping track of the development of my <a href="https://github.com/Jay-uu/pangenome-pipeline">Nextflow pipeline</a>. Working together with others in parallel was new, and a good exercise to get more familiar with the local repo, the staging area, the branches and the remote repo.</p>
</section>
<section id="quarto" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="quarto">Quarto</h2>
<p>Following a tutorial step-by-step sounds easy, but suddenly you miss a step (somehow) and you have to back track and do things over and over to try and solve whatever issue you caused by not being familiar enough with the tool/method/commands yet. The almost daily bioinfo-student experience. Taking a step back, staying calm and reading the instructions/error messages/output carefully usually helps. I’d say this blog is evidence for that!</p>


</section>
</section>

 ]]></description>
